something? -- tReflections and conclusions -- tReflections on neighbourhood planning: towards a progressive localism -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGovernments around the world are seeing the locality as a key arena for effecting changes in governance, restructuring state/civil society relations and achieving sustainable growth. This is the first book to critically analyse this shift towards localism in planning through exploring neighbourhood planning; one of the fastest growing, most popular and most contentious contemporary planning initiatives. Bringing together original empirical research with critical perspectives on governance and planning, the book engages with broader debates on the purposes of planning, the construction of active citizenship, the uneven geographies of localism and the extent to which power is actually being devolved. Setting this within an international context with cases from the US, Australia and France the book reflects on the possibilities for the emergence of a more progressive form of localism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCity planning. 0aCommunity life. 0aNeighborhood planning. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aBennett, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, Edited by Quintin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, Quintin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, Quintin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrownill, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrownill, Sue, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurnett, Amy, econtributor.4